review.review_data: Reviewed in the United States on August 10, 2021
review.title: It's good for a game but awful for a pokemon game
review.review: This specific seller's product is good; Though I'd personally recommend that if your considering getting this game because it's a pokemon game and, for that matter, the newest game of the series, I'd say that you should at least consider getting a different pokemon game instead. This one has barely any content and it feels like a massive cop-out in terms of world building and, like I said, the sheer amount of content. The entire world in the game just feels empty aside from useless (short-lasting) power-ups you find laying around literally everywhere. Theres no side quests, there's barely any main quest, and on that note, the main story in the game is incredibly hard to follow, at certain points the game just stops directly telling you where to go and just expects you to find your own way. Not saying you couldn't possibly enjoy the game, but just keep in mind that just because a lot of the other, more famous pokemon games might be old, their still much better than this one.

review.title: It supports old DS games.
review.review: What I like? Large screen, fun and easy to use interface (if you blow on the mic in the menu while hovered over an icon, the icon will spin), Backwards compatibility with old DS games (thank you for letting me play Pokemon Platinum again, and overall it's just a damn good handheld system, no surprise coming from Nintendo.What I don't like. The memory card you get with the game is fairly small so if you're going for digital downloads you'll only fit one game on it. Another thing I don't like is how it doesn't have a GameBoy game slot on the bottom like the old DS but I understand that that was never in the cards for the 3DS so I'm not counting that as a negative really just more of a "I wish it were there".Other than that its a damn good system that let me be a kid again by letting me play the games I used to play under by bed sheets at night.

review.review: I bought a used 3DS from Ichigo Ichie Japan, but when it arrived it seemed like it was brand new, without any scratches anywhere.The system is exactly what I wanted! It's smaller and more portable than the XL version and it's easily customizable. The box is colorful, which I like. There are a lot more themes on the Japanese theme shop than on the American one, too.Keep in mind the language can't be changed. The menus might be hard to navigate through if you don't know any Japanese. It doesn't play non-Japanese games, either.The only thing I have to complain about would be the volume slider--it feels kind of loose. I don't like how small the stylus is either, but it's fine.
